ce:section.ce:para:
To our knowledge, fluorescent sensors for probing the effect of thiram on the membrane structure of fungal cell and its quantitative detection in aqueous solution are rarely reported. In this article, L–asparagine and ethylenediamine (EDA) were used to synthesize a type of amine terminated CDs (CDs−NH2) by a facile, one–step microwave assisted pyrolysis. It is interesting that the fluorescence of CDs−NH2 can be quenched by Cu2+ via PET and the Cu2+– thiram complex via IFE (Scheme 1
                     ). By monitoring the fluorescence intensity of fungal cell via a confocal microscopy, the internalization of positively charged CDs−NH2 into fungal cells was promoted by thiram up to a certain point while the internalization of passively charged CDs (CDs−COO−) was not affected by thiram. On the other hand, the influx of Cu2+ into fungal cells was inspired by thiram up to a maximum, which was monitored using CDs−NH2 as a probe based on PET and IFE. Given that CDs−NH2 and Cu2+ are positively charged whereas CDs−COO− are passively charged, it suggests that the effect of thiram (the concentration in the range of 0.0 – 80.0 μM) on the membrane of fungal cell detected by the fluorescent CDs is stimulating the non–selective cation channel (Scheme 2
                     ). In addition, based on the IFE between CDs−NH2 and the Cu2+– thiram complex, an approach was built for the detection of thiram with high sensitivity and selectivity in the presence of excessive Cu2+.
